{{Nihongo|{{ill|Ikagashikoo|ja|伊香色雄|simple|User:Immanuelle/Ikagashikoo|en:draft}}|伊香色雄}} was a Japanese mythological figure.<ref name="Chamberlain-Basil-1882a" /> His sister was {{ill|Ikagashikome|en}}.
[[ja:伊香色雄]]
== Mythical narrative ==
During Emperor Sujin's reign, a major epidemic and political crisis<ref name="aston150–164">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=_oEfAAAAYAAJ|title=Nihongi: Chronicles of Japan from the Earliest Times to A.D. 697, Volume 2|author=Aston, William George.|date=1896|publisher=The Japan Society London|isbn=9780524053478|pages=150–164|author-link=William George Aston}}</ref> This led tim ho make major religious reforms to resolve it.<ref name="aston150–164" /> <ref name="aston150–164" /><ref name="Ellwood-1990a">{{Cite journal|last=Ellwood|first=Robert S.|date=1990|title=The Sujin Religious Revolution|url=https://www.jstor.org/stable/30234018|journal=Japanese Journal of Religious Studies|volume=17|issue=2/3|pages=199–217|doi=10.18874/jjrs.17.2-3.1990.199-217|issn=0304-1042|jstor=30234018}}</ref> .<ref name="aston150–164" />

Out of an abundance of caution, the Emperor also appointed {{Nihongo|{{ill|Ikagashikoo|ja|伊香色雄|simple|User:Immanuelle/Ikagashikoo|en:draft}}|伊香色雄}} as {{Nihongo|''kami-no-mono-akatsu-hito''|神班物者}}, or one who sorts the offerings to the gods.<ref name="Chamberlain-Basil-1882a">{{cite book |author=Chamberlain, Basil |url=http://www.sacred-texts.com/shi/kj/kj072.htm |title=''[SECT. LXV.—EMPEROR SŪ-JIN (PART III: STORY OF OHO-TATA-NE-KO'S BIRTH)]'' (''The Kojiki'') |publisher=Read before the Asiatic Society of Japan on April 12, May 10, and June 21, 1882, reprinted in 1919 |page=219 |quote=His Augustness Oho-tata-ne-ko&nbsp;... was the ancestor of the Dukes of Miwa and of the Dukes of Kamo. |author-link=Basil Chamberlain}}</ref>  {{ill|Ikagashikoo|ja|伊香色雄|simple|User:Immanuelle/Ikagashikoo|en:draft|8=fr}} became the ancestor of the now extinct {{ill|Mononobe clan|en}}.<ref name="Chamberlain-Basil-1882a" />

He first enshrined {{ill|Futsu-no-mitama|fr||en:draft||simple|User:Immanuelle/Futsu-no-Mitama}} at Isonokami Shrine.<ref> https://nippon-kichi.jp/article_list.do?ml_lang=en&p=1390</ref>

Afterwards, the Emperor ordered Ikashikio to make the many hiraka pots, like those of the Mononobe clan, into offerings to the deities (kamimatsurimono, or offerings at divine festivals), and to make Otataneko the chief priest of Omononushi-no-Okami and Ichiisonagaoichi the chief priest of Yamato-Okunitama-no-Kami. As a result, the epidemic subsided, the country became peaceful, the grains grew, and the peasants prospered. <ref>『日本書紀』崇神天皇7年11月13日条</ref>

This is the only scene in which Ikashikio appears, but from it we can see that Emperor Sujin implemented a policy of unity of religion and politics by worshiping the god of [[Mount Miwa]] [[Yamato Province|in Yamato Province]], thereby solidifying the foundation of the Yamato government and beginning to unify the surrounding countries. <ref>中央公論社『日本の歴史1』p281 - 282</ref>

